# Generation 8: identity & self-reflection — answered from the self-model
# the agent wrote into its own KB at birth (derived from real state).
> who are you?
< I am parrot0.
> what are you?
< I am parrot0.
> do you exist?
< Yes, I am parrot0.
# gen51 (C1): capabilities described in PLAIN language, grounded in the real
# module set (a module absent from the KB contributes nothing) — not the
# module(...) jargon dump it used to be.
> what can you do?
< I can answer questions about facts and rules, do simple arithmetic, reason about cause and effect, compare quantities, tell whether two things are the same, remember things you tell me, read a short passage and pull out facts, track what a pronoun refers to, continue a sequence you teach me.
# The reflexive payoff persists: the self-model is queried by the SAME logic
# engine as world knowledge — "who is a module?" resolves over module(X).
> who is a module?
< memory, self, compare, arith, quantity, cause, same, conj, gen, coref, bench, reader, knowledge, greet, farewell.
# Ordinary world knowledge still works alongside the self-model.
> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
> who is a man?
< socrates.
